<p>The written <b>history of Japan</b> begins with brief references of <i><a href="/wiki/Twenty-Four_Histories" title="Twenty-Four Histories">Twenty-Four Histories</a></i>, a collection of Chinese historical texts, in the 1st century AD. However, archaeological evidence indicates that people were living on the islands of Japan as early as the <a href="/wiki/Upper_Paleolithic" title="Upper Paleolithic">upper paleolithic</a> period.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Following the last <a href="/wiki/Ice-age" title="Ice-age" class="mw-redirect">ice-age</a>, around 12,000 BC, the rich <a href="/wiki/Ecosystem" title="Ecosystem">ecosystem</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Japanese_Archipelago" title="Japanese Archipelago">Japanese Archipelago</a> fostered human development. The earliest-known <a href="/wiki/Pottery" title="Pottery">pottery</a> belongs to the <a href="/wiki/J%C5%8Dmon" title="Jōmon" class="mw-redirect">Jōmon</a> period.</p>
